'''Wilson Dam''' is a  in  in the  of . It impounds . It is one of nine  (TVA) dams on the .  The dam was declared a  in 1966.<ref name="nhlsum"/><ref name="nrhpinv2">{{citation|title={{PDFlink|[http://pdfhost.focus.nps.gov/docs/NHLS/Text/66000147.pdf National Register of Historic Places Inventory-Nomination: Wilson Dam]|429&nbsp;<!-- application/pdf, 439478 bytes -->}}|date=February, 1976 |author=Polly M. Rettig and Horace J. Sheely, Jr. |publisher=National Park Service}} and {{PDFlink|[http://pdfhost.focus.nps.gov/docs/NHLS/Photos/66000147.pdf Accompanying 2 photos, 1 aerial and 1 from below, undated.]|235&nbsp;<!-- application/pdf, 241059 bytes -->}}</ref>
Construction on Wilson Dam began in 1918 and was completed in 1924.  The Wilson Dam actually predates the TVA, but was later placed under the authority of the TVA.  The dam is {{convert|137|ft|m}} high and {{convert|4541|ft|m}} across the .<ref name="tva">{{cite web | title = TVA Website | url = http://www.tva.gov/sites/wilson.htm | accessdate = 2007-05-16}}</ref>  The cost to build the dam was almost $47 million.<ref name="usace">{{cite web | title = US Army Corp of Engineers Website | url = http://www.lrn.usace.army.mil/history/wilson_lock_and_dam.htm | accessdate = 2007-05-16}}</ref>
The main  at Wilson Dam is {{convert|110|ft|m}} high by {{convert|600|ft|m}} long.  The maximum lift is {{convert|100|ft|m}}.  It is the highest single lift lock east of the <ref name="tva"/> An auxiliary lock has two {{convert|60|ft|m}} deep by {{convert|300|ft|m}} long chambers that operate in tandem.  Over 3,700 vessels pass through Wilson Dam's locks each year.<ref name="tva"/>
The generating capacity of Wilson dam is 675,400  of electricity.<ref name="tva"/>
